<HEAD>Zoo Director Pulls Panamanian Toads</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Note language in last graf</HEAD>
<DATELINE>COLUMBUS, Ohio (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An exhibit of Panamanian toads at the
Columbus Zoo has been pulled in the wake of the U.S. attempt to
oust Gen. Manuel Noriega from power, the zoo's director says.
   A group of zoo animals were scheduled for an appearance
Wednesday on ABC's ``Good Morning America,'' as part of a Christmas
show, said Jack Hanna, zoo director. But the fighting in Panama
pre-empted coverage of the exhibit.
   Hanna, in response to the fighting, then ordered that the toads
be taken off exhibit.
