<FIRST>u w PM-WeaponsPlan 1stLd-Writethru a0425 12-21 0612</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Weapons Plan, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0425,620</SECOND>
<HEAD>Scientists Challenge Administration View on Plutonium Needs</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Subs 3rd graf, The Energy Department, with department comment</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT BURNS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The United States has plenty of plutonium for
future use in nuclear weapons, and the Bush administration should
drop plans to spend $1 billion to expand supplies of the material,
a government advisory panel concludes.
   The conclusion published Wednesday by a special committee of the
National Research Council contradicts the administration's repeated
assertions to Congress that additional capacity to make
weapon-grade plutonium is vital to national security.
   The Energy Department, which owns the nation's defense nuclear
materials plants, issued a brief statement saying it had not fully
analyzed the document but would respond in detail within 30 days.
It said the report's recommendations ``appear to to fully
consistent with and supportive of'' actions already taken or
planned by the department.
   Former Energy Secretary John Herrington said during the Reagan
administration that the nation is ``awash in plutonium,'' but his
successor, James D. Watkins, had disavowed the statement. Watkins
contends that while current plutonium supplies are adequate, more
capacity will be needed in the coming decade.
   The research council said it saw no good reason either to
produce more virgin plutonium or to increase the capacity for
processing recycled plutonium from old weapons. It also challenged
Watkins' plan to build a $600 million plant in Idaho that would
convert reactor-grade plutonium to weapon-grade material.
   ``The Department of Energy should concentrate on making better
use of existing plutonium processing capacity as required and
postpone plans to construct additional capabilities,'' the report
said.
   Many private arms control groups have long advocated scaling
back plutonium operations.
   ``This is a certification by a semi-official body that you don't
need'' additional plutonium supplies, said David Albright, senior
staff scientist of the Federation of American Scientists.
   The report also criticized some aspects of the Energy
Department's overall management of the weapons complex, which
includes 17 major plants and laboratories in 12 states.
   On the subject of plutonium, the report noted that the United
States already has more than 20,000 nuclear weapons.
   ``The plutonium in these devices, plus that in the supply chain,
is obviously sufficient to supply a nuclear deterrent of the
existing size or even greater,'' it said.
   Official information on nuclear arms materials is classified.
   Watkins has advocated building a Special Isotope Separation
plant at the Idaho National Engineering Laboratory near Idaho
Falls. It would use a new vaporizing technology to convert
reactor-grade plutonium now stored near Richland, Wash., into
plutonium suitable for use in nuclear weapons.
   The scientific panel cited several reasons for scrapping the
Idaho project.
   ``To our knowledge, no compelling need for this material has
been demonstrated,'' its report said.
   It also said the Idaho facility, if built, could complicate
international efforts to limit the spread of nuclear arms. The new
isotope separation technology could be obtained by other countries
to convert fuel used in civilian nuclear reactors into high-grade
plutonium needed to build nuclear bombs, it said.
   John Spratt, D-S.C., chairman of a special House committee on
defense nuclear facilities, said in a telephone interview that the
report's conclusion about plutonium supplies, combined with
congressional resistance to adding more capacity, make it ``very
unlikely that the Special Isotope Separation plant will be built.''
   The report also said the Energy Department should drop plans to
spend $400 million renovating a building at the Rocky Flats plant
near Denver that recycles scrap plutonium into weapons-grade
material.
   The research council is an arm of the National Academy of
Sciences, a congressionally chartered group that conducts special
research at the request of the government.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP891221-0058 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-12-21-89 0948EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i PM-Sweden-Terrorist     12-21 0561</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Sweden-Terrorist,0578</SECOND>
<HEAD>Palestinian Suspected in Lockerbie Crash Convicted in Another Attack</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By EVA JANZON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>UPPSALA, Sweden (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Swedish court today convicted Mohammed
Abu Talb, a Palestinian suspected in the bombing of Flight 103, of
terrorism charges in connection with a fatal 1985 attack on an
airline office.
   The 35-year-old Palestinian was sentenced to life in prison for
the July 1985 bombing of a Northwest Airline office in Copenhagen.
The attack killed one person and wounded more than 20.
   A co-defendent, Marten Imandi, also 35, was convicted of charges
in connection with the Copenhagen attack and was sentenced to life
in prison.
   In Sweden, life imprisonment usually means 20 years at most.
   The court found Imandi guilty of murder for placing the fatal
explosive and convicted Abu Talb as an acessory.
   The convictions were part of a series legal actions concluded
today against a terrorist ring involved in bombings of U.S.,
Israeli and Jewish targets in Copenhagen and Amsterdam in 1985.
   They were acquitted of another bombing in Stockholm in 1986.
   The court also sentenced Mahmoud Al Mougrabi, 24, to six years
in prison and his 23-year-old brother Moustafa to a one-year
sentence for their involvement in the 1985 attacks.
   By coincidence, the verdict fell on the first anniversary of the
bombing of Flight 103, the Pan Am Boeing 747 that went down in
Lockerbie, Scotland, killing 270 people. Abu Talb is a suspect in
that bombing.
   Abu Talb's possible connection with the disaster surfaced when
it was established he had been in the Mediterranean island of Malta
two months before the explosion, when investigators believe the
bomb may have been prepared.
   Shreds from clothes wrapped around the bomb could match clothing
that Abu Talb brought back with him from Malta. Scottish police
seized 15 bags of clothing from his Uppsala home Nov. 27.
   Legal expers have said that if he was indicted for the Pan Am
explosion, he could be extradited to face trial in a foreign
country. He likely would be returned to Sweden to complete his
sentence, however.
   Abu Talb, who listed his birthplace as the Sabra refugee camp in
Beirut, Lebanon, is a former Egyptian army soldier who deserted to
join the Palestine Popular Struggle Front.
   Police have taken extra security precautions at airports around
Sweden this week in anticipation of a possible terror attack to
mark the Flight 103 anniversary. Experts warned that a guilty
verdict could heighten the risk.
   The 100-page decision by the court in Uppsala, 40 miles north of
Stockholm, was distributed at the courthouse without a hearing.
   Meanwhile, a Swedish newspaper reported today that further
evidence had been uncovered linking Abu Talb to the Pan Am
explosion over Lockerbie.
   The Dagens Nyheter newspaper said police found a 1988 calendar
with the date Dec. 21 circled, the day the plane was blasted by a
barometer-triggered explosive concealed in a radio-tape player
inside a suitcase.
   Scottish police tried to question Abu Talb on Tuesday, but he
refused to cooperate. The officers reportedly left Sweden, and were
due back after the holidays to continue their probe.
   Lord Fraser, Scotland's chief law officer, has said no
prosecutions were imminent in the case and no extraditions had been
requested. He was quoted in London last week as saying the United
States likely would claim jurisdiction and any trial would be held
there.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP891221-0059 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-12-21-89 0948EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-CovenantHouse     12-21 0465</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Covenant House,0479</SECOND>
<HEAD>Father of Accuser Says His Son is a Liar and Thief</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SAMUEL MAULL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The father of a former male prostitute who
accused the Rev. Bruce Ritter of misusing Covenant House money and
engaging in a sexual affair called his son an emotionally troubled
liar and a thief.
   ``And he has a pattern of intentionally hurting people who try
to help him, particularly people who've become a father figure to
him,'' Alton Kite said of his son, 25, who used the name Timothy
Warner when he made the allegations against the founder of Covenant
House, an acclaimed shelter for runaways.
   Kite said at a news conference Wednesday that his son's behavior
is caused by a diagnosed personality disorder and that he has
received psychiatric treatment.
   Kevin Lee Kite's charges of financial improprieties by the Roman
Catholic priest are being investigated by the district attorney's
office.
   Colleen Roche, a spokeswoman for the Manhattan district
attorney's office, had no comment on the elder Kite's remarks.
   The younger Kite, using another alias, was taken in by Covenant
House in New Orleans early last year. He was moved to New York
after he said he feared associates involved in drug running and
prostitution would kill him.
   Earlier this month, Kevin Kite charged that he and Ritter began
a sexual affair shortly after he was given haven here. The former
prostitute said that in return for sex, Ritter put him in an
apartment, enrolled him in a college, bought him clothes, a TV set
and a computer and gave him spending money.
   Ritter and other Covenant House officials denied the sexual
allegations and any financial wrongdoing.
   Kite's father, a junior-college accounting teacher in a town
near Dallas, said he decided to speak out after Covenant House
officials told him about his son's charges against Ritter.
   ``Kevin has caused people great problems and hardship with his
dishonesty before,'' Alton Kite said. ``I would like to help
someone who has suffered because of him.''
   He said he has spent thousands of dollars and suffered
immeasurable heartache trying to compensate his son's victims,
which include friends and neighbors.
   ``We're still paying for it,'' Kite said. ``His mother and I are
both teachers. We have almost no resources left, financially or
emotionally.''
   Kite said he had not spoken to his son since January.
   James Harnett, executive director of Covenant House, said that
the younger Kite ``lied to us about his name, lied to us about his
age, about his hometown and about his life being in danger. We also
know he's a thief _ his father has confirmed that.''
   Covenant House, founded by Ritter in New York, manages 17
shelters with more than 2,000 beds in the United States, Toronto
and Latin America.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
