<FILEID>AP-NR-12-21-89 1537EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-Yeutter-Farm     12-21 0570</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Yeutter-Farm,590</SECOND>
<HEAD>Yeutter Says Farmers Had Good Year</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DON KENDALL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Farm Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Farmers are closing out ``one of the best
years ever'' but will be subject to pivotal decisions in 1990 by
Congress and international trade negotiators, Agriculture Secretary
Clayton Yeutter said Thursday.
   Yeutter said 1989 income reached near-record levels,
agricultural exports have improved and the farm-credit situation
has eased for both lenders and borrowers.
   ``Net farm income will be either at or near a record for 1989,''
he said. ``The numbers are not fully determined yet, but certainly
it's been a very good year for American agriculture, one of the
best ever.''
   Most questions at Yeutter's year-end news conference related to
the Uruguay Round trade negotations under the General Agreement on
Tariffs and Trade, or GATT. Those talks are scheduled to conclude a
year from now.
   Yeutter was asked if he thought there would be a freer
international market by 1999, one of the goals sought by U.S.
negotiators, particularly for agricultural products.
   ``My personal assessment is that we have the best chance for
significant trade liberalization in agriculture that we've
experienced since the GATT began'' 40 years ago, he replied.
   ``I do believe it'll be a freer market 10 years from now than it
is today, and I also believe firmly that that will work to the
advantage of the American farmer.''
   Other questions related to legislation being drafted by Congress
to succeed the 1985 farm law that expires next year. Yeutter said
teams of Agriculture Department experts are working on plans for
the 1990 farm bill but did not divulge details.
   The United States at the GATT talks has sought a gradual
reduction and eventual elimination of all trade-distorting
subsidies and policies. But administration officials have adamantly
insisted that no U.S. programs would be scrapped unless other
countries did likewise.
   ``Though we may want to make some changes in all of these
programs in the 1990 farm bill because those may be desirable in
their own right ... we're not going to unilaterally disarm
internationally in that legislation,'' Yeutter said.
   ``So, whether we're talking about sugar, the wheat program or
any other program, I determined that we not forgo any of our
negotiating leverage in that 1990 legislative debate,'' he said.
``But at the same time, I am not prepared to accept the arguments
of any individual industry to the effect that says all changes in
the program are off-limits.''
   Yeutter, who joined President Bush's cabinet in January, was
U.S. trade representative in the Reagan administration and has been
in the thick of Uruguay round negotiations since they began Sept.
20, 1986, in Punta del Esta, Uruguay.
   ``I'm always an optimist, as you know,'' he said about the final
push during talks in 1990. ``But, certainly, I do not underestimate
the negotiating challenge. It will be significant indeed.''
   Yeutter said it would require ``an immense amount of effort and
a strong political commitment'' on the part of the United States,
the European Economic Community, Japan, the developing countries
and others to bring the GATT talks to a close a year from now.
   The private sector, including farm groups, also will be
important in reaching U.S. objectives during the negotiations, he
said.
   ``They can disagree about tactics ... or they can disagree about
particular nuances of the program,'' Yeutter said. ``But it's
important that we have broad support for our fundamental
objectives.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP891221-0105 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-12-21-89 1540EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-Brites     12-21 0413</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Brites,0426</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bright &amp; Brief</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SPRAGUE, Wash. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   This hard-luck town was destroyed by fire
in 1895, bypassed by the freeway in the late 1960s, flooded in the
'70s and dumped on by Mount St. Helens at the beginning of this
decade.
   But a state centennial project that transformed a vacant lot
into a plaza celebrating the town's heritage has earned some
residents national recognition.
   Eleven members of the Sprague-Lamont Camp Fire group and four
leaders went to Washington, D.C., this month to receive a
second-place award in the national Keep America Beautiful contest.
   The beautification project began last year when Camp Fire group
leader Rae Anna Victor decided Sprague needed something to stir the
community out of its doldrums and shake its downtrodden image. She
decided to start with a vacant lot covered with weeds, broken glass
and litter.
   The 35 boys and girls in the Camp Fire group were joined by
volunteers in raising $20,000 for the project through bake sales,
spaghetti feeds, raffles, turkey bingo and other fund-raisers.
   The lot was cleared and materials were donated to turn it into
the Sprague Centennial Plaza, complete with gazebo, trees and
grass. A 100-foot mural of 270 painted tiles tells the history of
the town, 35 miles southwest of Spokane.
   ``I get weepy when I even talk about it,'' said Gladys Engles,
80. ``There's more spirit and more Christmas lights in Sprague this
year than ever.''
   ``People used to come out of the drugstore and throw stuff into
the lot and it made the town look small and ugly,'' 11-year-old
Heather Wilken said. ``Now the plaza's made a lot of people stop
and see this town of ours.''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>HUNTINGTON, W.Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Richard Beckner won't slide down your
chimney, but for a small fee he'll bring packages to your door
dressed as Old St. Nick.
   Beckner is one of a few Postal Service employees who will
deliver packages this weekend dressed as Santa Claus. The Santa
service, which is not nationwide, costs $12.
   ``I'll take my time, do a little ho-ho with them and ask the
kids what they want for Christmas,'' Beckner said. ``You just don't
put the box down and say goodbye.''
   Joe Stultz, superintendent at the Huntington Post Office, said
two or three employees will be paid overtime on Saturday and Sunday
to deliver packages in Huntington dressed as Santa.
   ``We just decided to do something for the community,'' said
Stultz. ``We're losing money on it.''
</TEXT>
