<HEAD>Dollar, Gold Lower</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: AMer planned by 5:30 p.m. EST</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar finished lower against major currencies
in Europe Thursday in light pre-holiday trading. Gold prices also
fell.
   Currency strategists said there was no underlying reason for the
dollar's behavior, though some U.S.-based strategists said talk of
lower interest rates in the United States may have played a role. A
drop in interest rates would make dollar-denominated investments
worth less.
   The U.S. invasion of Panama and unrest in Romania appeared to
have had little impact on the U.S. currency, money brokers said.
   In London, the British pound rose to $1.6125 from $1.6052 late
Wednesday.
