<FIRST>d f EC-Inflation     12-21 0157</FIRST>
<SECOND>EC-Inflation,0163</SECOND>
<HEAD>Slowed to 0.4 Percent in November</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BRUSSELS, Belgium (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Consumer prices in the 12 European
Community nations rose by an average of 0.4 percent in November,
slowing from a 0.6 percent increase in October, the economic bloc
said Thursday.
   It's statistical bureau said EC inflation would be about 5.5
percent for 1989, up from 4.4 percent in 1988 and 3.4 percent in
1987.
   The highest price increases in November were in Portugal, with 1
percent, and in Britain and Greece with 0.9 percent each.
   Prices were unchanged in the Netherlands, while the consumer
price index fell 0.1 percent in Belgium.
   The EC said rates of inflation for the 12 European countries in
1989 were as follows: Greece, 14 percent; Portugal, 11.5 percent;
Britain, 7.5 percent; Spain, 7.0 percent; Italy, 6.0 percent;
Denmark, 4.8 percent; Ireland, 4.7 percent; Luxembourg, 3.8
percent; France, 3.5 percent; Belgium, 3.3 percent; West Germany,
3.0 percent; Netherlands, 1.2 percent.
</TEXT>
