<FILEID>AP-NR-12-21-89 1815EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f AM-MoneySupply     12-21 0361</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Money Supply,0371</SECOND>
<HEAD>Money Supply Rises</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The three broadest measures of the nation's
money supply rose in the week ended Dec. 11, the Federal Reserve
Board reported Thursday.
   The Fed said the narrowest measure of the money supply, M1, rose
to a seasonally adjusted $793.1 billion from $789.7 billion the
previous week.
   The measure known as M2 rose to a seasonally adjusted $3,212.2
billion from $3,207.4 billion.
   An even broader measure, M3, rose to a seasonally adjusted
$4,059.3 billion from $4,056.6 billion.
   M1 includes cash in circulation, deposits in checking accounts
and non-bank travelers checks. M2 is M1 plus accounts like savings
deposits and money-market mutual funds. M3 is M2 plus less-liquid
accounts, such as certificates of deposit in minimum denominations
of $100,000.
   In judging its monetary policy, the Fed has indicated it is
monitoring the value of the dollar, commodity prices and the
difference between short- and long-term interest rates. It also has
shifted its attention from M1 to the two broader money supply
measures.
   The annual growth rate in M2 so far this year is 4.4 percent,
which is within the Fed's target range of 3 percent to 7 percent.
The annual growth rate in M3 is 3.0 percent, which is below the
Fed's target range of 3.5 percent to 7.5 percent. The Fed has not
set a target for M1 growth since early 1987.
   For the latest 13 weeks, M2 averaged $3,184.3 billion, a 7.9
percent seasonally adjusted annual rate of gain from the previous
13 weeks. M3 averaged $4,034.0 billion, up 3.3 percent, while M1
rose 6.1 percent to an average of $787.8 billion.
   In other reports:
   _The Federal Reserve said bank borrowings from the Federal
Reserve System at the discount window, excluding extended credit,
averaged $169 million a day in the week ended Wednesday, up from
$110 million the previous week.
   _The Federal Reserve Bank of St. Louis reported that the
monetary base, the seasonally adjusted total of member bank
reserves held at Federal Reserve banks and cash in bank vaults and
in circulation, was $294.5 billion in the two-week period ended
Dec. 13, up from $293.4 billion two weeks earlier.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP891221-0266 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-12-21-89 2044EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f AM-ICI-Atlas     12-21 0205</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-ICI-Atlas,0213</SECOND>
<HEAD>ICI to Buy Atlas Powder</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WILMINGTON, Del. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Chemical products giant ICI PLC
announced Thursday it has agreed to buy Tyler Corp.'s Atlas Powder
Co. to strengthen its position in commercial explosives and
detonator products businesses.
   The agreement is valued at $193 million with ICI assuming $58
million in debts and paying $135 million to Tyler shareholders. The
deal is expected to be completed in early 1990.
   Atlas is a wholly-owned subsidiary of the Dallas-based Tyler.
ICI is based in London. Its American operation is ICI Americas,
headquartered in Wilmington.
   ``The United States is the world's largest commercial explosives
market and this acquisition will significantly enhance the
geographical coverage of ICI's international explosives business
and provide additional product opportunities arising from the
introduction of ICI technology into the U.S. marketplace,'' said
Bob Clark, a top executive of ICI explosives.
   ICI's explosives business has been based in Toronto since 1988.
Last year, the business had sales of $655 million. The business
employs about 8,000 people worldwide.
   Atlas, founded in 1912, manufactures and sells commercial
explosives and detonator products almost exclusively in the United
States. Atlas operates in 35 states and employs about 1,500 people.
It had sales of $198 million in 1988.
</TEXT>
